{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16741"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16741"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.04,0.07,0.54,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89196"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2188"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4068"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4199"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12217"},{"type":"tags","id":"12220"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43654"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent concerned about not having started menstruation. She has noticed breast development and sparse axillary and pubic hair growth. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with her boyfriend and uses condoms for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is 175 cm tall with normal female breast development (Tanner stage 4) and normal external female genitalia. Pelvic examination reveals a short vagina. A transabdominal ultrasound shows absent uterus and ovaries. Blood tests reveal testosterone 25 nmol/L (0.5-2.6), follicle stimulating hormone 2.5 IU/L (1.0-8.0), luteinizing hormone 12 IU/L (2.0-12.0), and oestradiol 120 pmol/L (70-530).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Androgen insensitivity syndrome","Polycystic ovary syndrome","Turner syndrome","M\u00fcllerian agenesis","Constitutional delay of puberty"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with primary amenorrhoea, normal female external phenotype, and absent uterus, which is characteristic of complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS). The elevated testosterone level in the male range with normal female external genitalia strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Eandrogen insensitivity syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. These individuals have a 46,XY karyotype but are phenotypically female due to complete resistance to androgens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u00fcllerian agenesis\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as Mayer-Rokitansky-K\u00fcster-Hauser syndrome) would present similarly with primary amenorrhoea and absent uterus, but these patients would have normal female (46,XX) karyotype and normal female hormone levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstitutional delay of puberty\u003C/strong\u003E would present with delayed onset of all secondary sexual characteristics, not just amenorrhoea. These patients would have a uterus visible on imaging and normal female hormone levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with irregular periods rather than primary amenorrhoea. While testosterone may be mildly elevated, it would not be in the male range, and these patients would have a visible uterus on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETurner syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (45,X) typically presents with short stature and primary amenorrhoea, but these patients would have low oestrogen levels and poor development of secondary sexual characteristics. They would have a visible, though possibly hypoplastic, uterus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of AIS involves careful counselling regarding the diagnosis, psychological support, and consideration of gonadectomy after puberty due to the risk of malignant transformation in the intra-abdominal testes. Oestrogen replacement therapy is typically required after gonadectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete androgen insensitivity syndrome presents with primary amenorrhoea in a phenotypically female patient with female external genitalia but absent uterus and upper vagina.","The karyotype in complete androgen insensitivity syndrome is 46,XY despite female phenotype.","Testosterone levels are typically in the male range in androgen insensitivity syndrome, but there is no virilisation due to androgen receptor dysfunction."],"references":["Conway GS. Primary Amenorrhoea [Internet]. O\u0026G Magazine. 2017 [cited 2024 Dec 1];19(3). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/3-19/primary-amenorrhoea/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89196"}},"question":{"data"